comments.body:
If I can suggest a slightly different linked-list design, which would avoid some conditionals.

A doubly-linked, circular, list. The sentinel is both the first and the last element of the list of flagged entries. Every non-flagged entry is also a linked list, containing just itself. In this case, adding/removing from the flagged list is just concatenating/splicing linked lists, which can be done without conditions/edge cases.

```c++
CCoinsCacheEntry() noexcept
{
    ...
    m_prev = this;
    m_next = this;
}

/** Insert this after other. */
void InsertAfter(CCoinsCacheEntry* other) noexcept
{
    auto other_next = other->m_next;
    std::swap(other->m_next, m_prev->m_next);
    std::swap(m_prev, other_next->m_prev);
}

/** Insert this before other. */
void InsertBefore(CCoinsCacheEntry* other)
{
    auto other_prev = other->m_prev;
    std::swap(other->m_prev, m_next->m_prev);
    std::swap(m_next, other_m_prev->m_next);
}

/** Make this a singleton list. Can be done on entries that are already singletons. */
void TakeOut()
{
    auto old_prev = m_prev;
    std::swap(m_next->m_prev, m_prev);
    std::swap(old_prev->m_next, m_next);
}
```

